Anonymous Tue 04 Apr 2023 20:11:57 No.55546778 Report
Quoted By: >>55546828 >>55546896 >>55547308
>>55532807
>I want music in my game but don’t have music knowledge
Here are your options from my experience
>1. Learn music
There are no copyright issues and it has the most soul. But it's the most time-consuming. Will probably be shitty due to your inexperience
>2. Pay freelance artists to make music for you
At least the music will be polished and original. Downsides are the product/comms are not personal to your employee and it costs a lot of money
>3. Ask local musician anons in the thread or on /mu/ for free music.
Upside is, it's free music and the Anon will only join if he has interest in your game to begin with. Soundtrack will be original. Soul. Downside is you'll get a lot of rejections and have to deal with the schedule/whims of your musician.
>4. Download MIDI rips of songs you like
Easy to do. Freedom to choose your soundtrack. Cons: No soul whatsoever. Mild risk of copyright issues depending on how much you transform the track
>5. Find songs with friendly CC licenses
Pros: Some freedom of choice. Mild soul, albeit the soul of an independent artist. No copyright problems. Cons: The soundtrack is unoriginal, often sounds generic. The search for good, free music can be time-consuming.
>6. Use copyrighted music in your game
Pros: complete freedom of choice. Quickest and easiest. Cons: Unoriginality. Illegality. If your game ever gets popular it could get taken down or worse, although I've never seen indie games get sued at this scale.

Anonymous Tue 04 Apr 2023 21:33:37 No.55548344 Report
Quoted By:
>>55547308
You're right, these two are notable. We can call these 7 and 8
>7. AI music
Pros: Quick and easy if you know the right tools. Music is original. No copyright issues (probably)
Cons: Zero soul whatsoever. "Pay to play" options exist and are cheaper than musicians, but communication with the AI is poorer and having it revise the music is difficult or impossible.
>8. Have the user make their own playlist
This is a very niche strategy. It works when the game only needs to serve 1 or 2 moods. Good for open-world games, explorers and sandboxes, and anything else with limited environment.
Cons: There's no fucking soundtrack. If you do a hybrid "folder + soundtrack" approach like MSC, then the jukebox functionality can work. But if there are few or no pre-existing songs, people will just put on Spotify while they play. Most will ignore the jukebox entirely.
Oh, and forget about games with more than one mood. Anything with boss fights, changes in story or environment, or character arcs will be crippled because any song can play anywhere.
